        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1977-05-31T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1977-05-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="76"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d76">
                <head>76. Memorandum From Acting Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_CW_1"
                        >Christopher</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1"
                        >Carter</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d76fn1">Source: Carter Library, National
                        Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material, Subject File, Box 18, Evening Reports
                        (State): 5/77. Secret. In the upper right-hand corner of the first page of
                        the memorandum, <persName corresp="#p_CH_1">Carter</persName> wrote: “To
                        Warren, J.”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1977-05-31">May 31, 1977</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to India.]</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">India</hi>. Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_GRF_1"
                        >Goheen</persName> raised the Tarapur question in his initial meeting with
                    Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_DM_1">Desai</persName>. <persName
                        corresp="#p_DM_1">Desai</persName> promptly accepted the three conditions
                    you set for recommending approval of the long-pending shipment of low-enriched
                    fuel: (1) Indian willingness to maintain <gloss target="#t_IAEA_1">IAEA</gloss>
                    safeguards on Tarapur,<note n="2" xml:id="d76fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_CH_1">Carter</persName> underlined: “maintain <gloss
                            target="#t_IAEA_1">IAEA</gloss> safeguards on Tarapur.” See <ref
                            target="#d74">Document 74</ref>.</note> (2) <persName corresp="#p_DM_1"
                        >Desai</persName>’s personal assurance that U.S. fuel would not be used in a
                    nuclear explosive device,<note n="3" xml:id="d76fn3">
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> underlined: “U.S. fuel would
                        not be used in a nuclear explosive device.”</note> and (3) agreement to
                    enter into negotiations with us on non-proliferation questions.<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d76fn4">
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> underlined: “enter into
                        negotiations with us on non-proliferation questions.”</note>
                    <persName corresp="#p_DM_1">Desai</persName> told <persName corresp="#p_GRF_1"
                        >Goheen</persName> he was critical of the manner in which Mrs. <persName
                        corresp="#p_GI_1">Gandhi</persName> conducted the 1974 Indian test, that he
                    was not planning to authorize another test,<note n="5" xml:id="d76fn5">
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> underlined: “not planning to
                        authorize another test.”</note> and that if the question came up he would
                    consult with us.<note n="6" xml:id="d76fn6">In the left-hand margin next to this
                        paragraph, <persName corresp="#p_CH_1">Carter</persName> wrote: “ok—I would
                        like this in writing.”</note>
                </p>
                <p>On the basis of <persName corresp="#p_DM_1">Desai</persName>’s positive response,
                    our recommendation to the Nuclear Regulatory Commission to license the fuel
                    shipment will go forward this week. <persName corresp="#p_NJ_2">Joseph
                        Nye</persName> is tentatively slated to meet with the Indian Foreign
                    Secretary in London June 10 to arrange to open the non-proliferation
                    negotiations.</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to India.]</p>
            </div>
